      A different methodology that could be adopted for this study could start with the problem selection. Selecting problems from different categories of difficulty and also from a widely used coding platform, like Leetcode, would increase the external validity of the study, as it would cover a larger variety of problems, not just in terms of difficulty, but also in terms of algorithmic categories. Talking about selecting the final problems for the analysis, the original methodology is more strict, because it only considers problems for which the LLMs provided a correct solution using the original prompt from the EvoVal leaderboard, without any possibility of regeneration. An alternative would be to implement a regeneration cycle, in which each LLM is reprompted up to 25 times, each regeneration iteration including the execution feedback from the last code version that was produced. The first correct solution that would be produced in this cycle would be considered for the analysis. This can indeed cause unfair comparisons, as some LLMs that might manage to generate a correct solution after very few reprompts will be compared to LLMs that might have needed a lot more attempts. The first case represents an "innate" capacity of the LLM to generate a correct solution, while the second case represents more of a "learning" capacity. On the other hand, this option also allows for a much larger variety of problems to be included in the analysis. The paper's methodology might result in only the easier problems from the chosen difficult category being selected, as those problems give higher chances to LLMs to successfully generate a correct solution on the first try. Besides this, it also doesn't represent a realistic scenario, as in the real world, developers usually keep reprompting the LLM until they get a satisfactory solution. Besides the problem selection, what could be additionally done in order to gather even more useful results would be to create different benchmark sets that would include specific LLMs and specific problems for which those LLMs have given a correct solution. However, this could drastically increase the complexity and the time needed for the experiment execution.

      When it comes to the actual measurement of energy efficiency, a different approach that could be adopted for this study would be to statistically analyze the energy efficiency of the code generated by the LLMs. Instead of executing the Python code generated by the LLMs for each problem on different hardware platforms, this method relies on structural code parsing. The code generated by each LLM would be transformed into a tokenized data structure, namely an Abstract Syntax Tree (AST) @sun_abstract_syntax_tree_2023. From this structural tree, specific language features like loop nesting, keyword frequencies, operator densities, and conditional branch limits are statically extracted as numerical features. These static features are fed directly into a pre-trained machine learning model, which is also less energy-intensive (such as a Random Forest), that maps structural complexity code fingerprints directly to a predictive energy footprint value, skipping the execution phase completely.


      The dilemma between choosing one of the two is based on multiple trade-offs:

